{
  "computedAt": "2026-04-30T12:28:28Z",
  "pattern_id": "P23",
  "pattern_name": "POV duration per character",
  "description": "Per-book distribution of consecutive POV-run lengths per character, measured in both scenes and beats. Pure compute on beats.jsonl + scenes.jsonl.",
  "rationale": "Feeds the planner's POV-rotation prior. Currently the planner emits a per-chapter POV without an explicit constraint on how long a single POV holds before rotating. If the corpus has a stable POV-hold length distribution, that's a directional planner constraint on how aggressively to rotate POV across the chapter outline.",
  "methodology": {
    "pov_inference_v1_rejected": "Per-beat name-mention density was tried first but produced median POV-run length of 1 beat (81-84% length-1 runs) -- implausible for Salvatore's known close-third single-scene-POV style. Root cause: per-beat mention counting is dominated by whoever's named/spoken-to in that beat, even if narrating a different character's POV. Rejected.",
    "pov_inference_v2_used": "Scene-anchored: for each scene, aggregate the full scene text + 3x-weighted beat summaries, count canonical-character mentions, pick the dominant. Salvatore's scene-level POV is monolithic (one character per scene), so scene-level inference is the natural granularity. Cross-validated by spot-check + by Drizzt holding a stable 25-29% POV share across all three books.",
    "run_definition": "A POV run is a maximal sequence of consecutive scenes (in document order: scene_idx within book) holding the same canonical POV character. We report run lengths in BOTH scenes (the natural unit of inference) and beats (the planner-relevant unit, since beat-expander operates per beat). None-POV scenes (no canonical-character match) are carry-forward (3-7% of scenes per book).",
    "carry_forward_rationale": "Scenes with no detectable canonical character are typically descriptive interludes or narrator-voice exposition that don't represent a POV switch. Carrying the prior POV forward yields stable runs.",
    "limitation": "POV is inferred from name-mention density, not narrative tag. The heuristic is reliable for scenes anchored on a single character (the dominant case); confidence drops for ensemble scenes (multiple Companions interacting), where the scene's POV may be the most-mentioned-but-not-the-actual-narrative-perspective character. Validated by sanity-checks: Drizzt is top POV ~25-29% across all books; Akar Kessell is top non-Companion POV in book 1 but absent from books 2-3; Artemis Entreri appears as major POV in books 2-3 but absent from book 1. All matches known canon."
  },
